text: hi everyone Anthony Fantino here the
Internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new Tycho album
awake this is the 4th full-length LP I
believe from California based music
producer Tycho cool it has been a little
while since we last heard from this guy
I believe back in 2011 with his last
flight they'll be dive which at least in
my opinion seemed like one of the last
dying breaths of what we remember as
chill wave really light summery Pleasant
easygoing electronic instrumentals on
this thing loaded with atmosphere and
feel good vibes sweet melodies
shimmering synthesizers nothing too
gripping nothing too offensive in my
opinion music for those who don't want
their buzz harshed for me it's music
that sets a mood it's not bad for a song
or two but it tends to just fall in the
background for me as I listen to an
entire record of this stuff overall the
LP is just a little too pastel for me
given that I was not really looking
forward to what Tycho was going to do on
this new full-length LP of his
especially since it looks like it I
don't know it's kind of like a different
version or a rather a rendition with the
repeat of the sunset album art but just
kind of in a more minimalistic way
however I will say that awake is a
pretty impressive change of pace for
Tycho he moves from what sounds like a
single lone bedroom producer to a full
band there are a lot of tight
instrumental grooves on the cell peace
snappy crisp drum sounds shimmering
twinkly guitars warm bass lines I love
the tone of the bass on this thing a lot
of the bass lines are driving and have
kind of a picked sound to them not
fingered and for the most part taiko
just kind of keeps it instrumental as
usual and this time around instead of
just feeling like an average chill waver
just hazy electronic music project taiko
seems a lot more like a more pleasant on
the ear version of post-rock act
sixty-five days of static or maserati or
maybe like battles with zero
eccentricity or experimentation and
that's essentially what this record
comes down to for me Tyco has made a
major change to the instrumental
qualities of his music but he has
maintained that really sort of chill
laid-back vibe
I think the instrumentation is a lot
more tangible which overall makes these
very chill Pleasant instrumentals more
engaging for me but there are still a
considerable amount of songs on this
record that to me are nothing more than
kind of uneventful I do think that live
more raw instrumental element does add
positive qualities to this record like
on the song die where I'm here a lot of
explorative synthesizer leads playing on
the track I also love the progression of
this song from it's very subtle start to
some of the more heavy beats and layered
synthesizers on the back end and I
actually think there's a decent amount
of variety among these tracks to like on
the song apogee which surprisingly
incorporates some drum and bass breaks
into its rhythm section but even with
all this production quality being
improved and some different stylistic
influences coming into the recipe on
this taiko album I can't say that this
record goes out on a limb even once or
even stirs up a really exhilarating
moment and still I I don't think that is
Tycho's mo I don't really think I can
expect that from a taiko record into the
future but who knows I didn't expect
sort of more tangible instrumentation to
turn up on this record and here we are
while I do think this record has a lot
going for it I prefer just a bit more
grit and eccentricity in my music that's
all at least what taiko continues to do
in terms of his style and his sound on
this record is sounding a lot more
intricate and engaging I'm feeling a
decent strong six on this thing
transition if you've given this record a
listen what did you think of it did you
love it did you hate it why what do you
think I should review next and that's
about it
Anthony Fantana music review forever
